Biology is the [scientific study](/Scientific_study) of [life](/Life) and, by extension, all living [organisms](/Organism). It's a vast, sprawling landscape of a [natural science](/Natural_science), a discipline that interrogates the very essence of existence through a kaleidoscope of fields and a bedrock of unifying principles. Biology doesn't just describe; it explains the intricate dance of structure, function, growth, the baffling [origin](/History_of_life) of it all, the relentless march of [evolution](/Evolution), and the glorious, chaotic tapestry of life's distribution across our planet. At its heart, it’s anchored by five fundamental pillars: the [cell](/Cell_(biology)) as life's irreducible unit, the [genes](/Gene) and the mechanism of [heredity](/Heredity) that carry the torch of inheritance, [evolution](/Evolution) as the engine of [biological diversity](/Biological_diversity), the ceaseless flow of [energy](/Energy) that fuels every biological process, and the delicate, constant balancing act of maintaining internal stability, known as [homeostasis](/Homeostasis).

Biology's gaze sweeps across every conceivable [level of organization](/Biological_organisation), from the minuscule machinations of [molecules](/Molecule) and cells to the grand architecture of organisms, the collective pulse of [populations](/Population), and the interconnected webs of [ecosystems](/Ecosystem). Its subdisciplines are legion, each a specialized lens: [molecular biology](/Molecular_biology) dissecting the molecular machinery, [physiology](/Physiology) exploring the functions of living systems, [ecology](/Ecology) examining the interactions between organisms and their environments, [evolutionary biology](/Evolutionary_biology) tracing the grand narrative of change, [developmental biology](/Developmental_biology) charting the journey from a single cell to a complex being, and [systematics](/Systematics) striving to catalogue and understand the relationships between all life. These fields employ a formidable arsenal of methods, from patient [observation](/Scientific_method) and rigorous [experimentation](/Scientific_method) to the elegant logic of [mathematical modeling](/Mathematical_modeling). The bedrock of modern biology is undeniably the theory of evolution by [natural selection](/Natural_selection), a concept so profound it was independently conceived by [Charles Darwin](/Charles_Darwin). This, coupled with our ever-deepening molecular understanding of genes encoded within [DNA](/DNA), has revolutionized our perception of life. The landmark discovery of the [structure of DNA](/Structure_of_DNA) and the subsequent explosion in [molecular genetics](/Molecular_genetics) have not only transformed biology but have also paved the way for groundbreaking applications in [medicine](/Medicine), [agriculture](/Agriculture), [biotechnology](/Biotechnology), and [environmental science](/Environmental_science).

Life, as we know it, is thought to have clawed its way into existence on [Earth](/Earth) over 3.7 billion years ago. The sheer variety of organisms today is staggering—from the microscopic resilience of [archaea](/Archaea) and [bacteria](/Bacteria) to the sprawling complexity of multicellular [plants](/Plant), [fungi](/Fungi), and [animals](/Animal). [Biologists](/Biologist) meticulously classify these life forms, weaving them into [taxonomic](/Taxonomy_(biology)) and [phylogenetic](/Phylogenetic) frameworks that reflect both shared characteristics and evolutionary kinship. These organisms don't exist in isolation; they engage in constant, dynamic interactions within [ecosystems](/Ecosystem), playing vital roles in the ceaseless flow of [energy](/Ecological_energetics) and the cyclical dance of [nutrient cycling](/Nutrient_cycling). Biology is a discipline in perpetual motion, a field that thrives on new discoveries and the relentless refinement of our understanding, all while grappling with humanity's most pressing challenges: [disease](/Disease), the looming specter of [climate change](/Climate_change), and the accelerating loss of [biodiversity](/Biodiversity_loss).

### Etymology

The word "biology" itself is a linguistic artifact, a fusion of ancient Greek roots. It draws from βίος (bíos), meaning 'life'—a concept echoing the Proto-Indo-European root *gwei-, signifying "to live." The second component, λογία (logia), translates to 'study of.' The precise moment this compound entered common usage is a bit murky, but its appearance in print can be traced back to Volume 3 of Michael Christoph Hanow's *Philosophiae naturalis sive physicae dogmaticae: Geologia, biologia, phytologia generalis et dendrologia* in 1766. However, the term "biology" as we understand it today seems to have been independently coined by several figures. Thomas Beddoes employed it in 1799, Karl Friedrich Burdach in 1800, Gottfried Reinhold Treviranus in his 1802 work *Biologie oder Philosophie der lebenden Natur*, and Jean-Baptiste Lamarck in his *Hydrogéologie*, also published in 1802.

### History

The very origins of scientific inquiry, including the nascent fields that would eventually coalesce into biology, can be traced back to the cradles of civilization in [ancient Egypt](/Ancient_Egypt) and [Mesopotamia](/Mesopotamia), around 3000 to 1200 [BCE](/Common_Era). These early civilizations laid groundwork that would profoundly influence the development of [natural philosophy](/Natural_philosophy) in [ancient Greece](/Ancient_Greece). Philosophers like [Aristotle](/Aristotle) (384–322 BCE) made monumental contributions, delving into the complexities of biological causation and meticulously cataloging the astonishing diversity of life. His successor, [Theophrastus](/Theophrastus), is credited with initiating the scientific study of plants. During the [medieval Islamic world](/Science_in_the_medieval_Islamic_world), scholars like [al-Jahiz](/Al-Jahiz) (781–869) and [Al-Dīnawarī](/Al-D%C4%ABnawar%C4%AB) (828–896) made significant contributions to botany, while [Rhazes](/Muhammad_ibn_Zakar%C4%ABya_R%C4%81zi) (865–925) explored [anatomy](/Anatomy) and [physiology](/Physiology). The medical traditions of Islamic scholars, deeply rooted in Greek philosophy, were particularly robust, while natural history largely drew from Aristotelian thought.

The true acceleration of biological discovery began with Anton van Leeuwenhoek's ingenious improvements to the [microscope](/Microscope). Suddenly, a hidden universe unfurled: [spermatozoa](/Spermatozoa), bacteria, and a dazzling array of microscopic life were revealed. Jan Swammerdam's meticulous investigations sparked renewed interest in [entomology](/Entomology) and advanced techniques in microscopic [dissection](/Dissection) and [staining](/Staining). These microscopic revelations had a seismic impact on biological thought. By the early 19th century, the [cell](/Cell_(biology)) emerged as a central concept. Matthias Jakob Schleiden and Theodor Schwann championed the now-universal tenets that (1) the cell is the fundamental unit of all organisms and (2) individual cells possess all the characteristics of life. They did, however, initially resist the idea that (3) all cells arise from the division of pre-existing cells, clinging to the concept of [spontaneous generation](/Spontaneous_generation). It was the work of Robert Remak and Rudolf Virchow that solidified the third tenet, and by the 1860s, the three pillars of [cell theory](/Cell_theory) were widely accepted.

Concurrently, the meticulous work of natural historians focused on taxonomy and classification. Carl Linnaeus published his foundational [taxonomy](/Taxonomy_(biology)) in 1735, followed by the introduction of [scientific names](/Binomial_nomenclature) for species in the 1750s. Georges-Louis Leclerc, Comte de Buffon, challenged the rigid categorization of species, proposing that living forms were more fluid and even hinting at the possibility of [common descent](/Common_descent).

The seeds of evolutionary thought were sown by Jean-Baptiste Lamarck, who presented a comprehensive theory of evolution. The British [naturalist](/Natural_history) Charles Darwin, synthesizing the biogeographical insights of Alexander von Humboldt, the geological principles of Charles Lyell, the demographic observations of Thomas Malthus, and his own extensive fieldwork, formulated a powerful evolutionary theory driven by [natural selection](/Natural_selection). Independently, Alfred Russel Wallace arrived at remarkably similar conclusions through his own reasoning and evidence.

The foundations of modern [genetics](/Genetics) were laid by Gregor Mendel in 1865, outlining the fundamental principles of biological inheritance. While the profound significance of his work remained largely unrecognized until the early 20th century, the [modern synthesis](/Modern_synthesis_(20th_century)) in the mid-20th century unified Darwinian evolution with classical genetics. The pivotal experiments of Alfred Hershey and Martha Chase in the 1940s and early 1950s pointed towards [DNA](/DNA) as the carrier of hereditary information, the units that would come to be known as [genes](/Gene). The discovery of the double-helical structure of DNA by James Watson and Francis Crick in 1953, building on research with model organisms like [viruses](/Virus) and bacteria, heralded the dawn of [molecular genetics](/Molecular_genetics). Since then, biology has expanded dramatically in the molecular realm. The deciphering of the [genetic code](/Genetic_code) by Har Gobind Khorana, Robert W. Holley, and Marshall Warren Nirenberg marked another monumental leap. The ambitious [Human Genome Project](/Human_Genome_Project), launched in 1990, aimed to map the entire human [genome](/Genome), promising unprecedented insights into our biological blueprint.

### Chemical Basis

At the most fundamental level, all organisms are intricate assemblies of [chemical elements](/Chemical_element). The vast majority of an organism's mass—around 96%—is composed of [oxygen](/Oxygen), [carbon](/Carbon), [hydrogen](/Hydrogen), and [nitrogen](/Nitrogen). The remaining portion is largely accounted for by [calcium](/Calcium), [phosphorus](/Phosphorus), [sulfur](/Sulfur), [sodium](/Sodium), [chlorine](/Chlorine), and [magnesium](/Magnesium). These elements combine to form [compounds](/Chemical_compound), with water being a prime example of a substance absolutely fundamental to life. [Biochemistry](/Biochemistry) is the discipline dedicated to understanding the complex [chemical processes](/Chemical_process) that occur within and between living [organisms](/Organism). Complementing this, [molecular biology](/Molecular_biology) delves into the molecular underpinnings of biological activity, exploring how molecules are synthesized, modified, and interact at the cellular level.

#### Water

Life itself is believed to have emerged from the primordial oceans of Earth, which formed approximately 3.8 billion years ago. Water, even now, remains the most abundant molecule within every organism. Its critical importance to life stems from its remarkable capacity as a [solvent](/Solvent). It can dissolve a wide array of solutes, from simple [ions](/Ion) like sodium and [chloride](/Chloride) to more complex small molecules, forming [aqueous](/Aqueous_solution) [solutions](/Solution_(chemistry)) where [chemical reactions](/Chemical_reaction) essential for life can readily occur.

Water's molecular structure—a small, bent [polar molecule](/Chemical_polarity) formed by two hydrogen atoms covalently bonded to a single oxygen atom (H₂O)—is key to its properties. The polarity means the oxygen atom carries a slight negative charge, while the hydrogen atoms bear a slight positive charge. This polarity facilitates the formation of hydrogen bonds between water molecules, giving water its remarkable [cohesion](/Cohesion_(chemistry)). This cohesion contributes to phenomena like [surface tension](/Surface_tension), the force that makes water molecules cling together at the liquid's surface. Water also exhibits [adhesion](/Adhesion), the ability to stick to other polar or charged surfaces. Uniquely, water is denser as a liquid than as a solid (ice). This property allows ice to float, insulating the water below and preventing aquatic ecosystems from freezing solid. Water's capacity to absorb substantial amounts of energy before its temperature rises significantly is due to its high [specific heat capacity](/Specific_heat_capacity), far exceeding that of many other solvents like [ethanol](/Ethanol). This thermal stability is crucial for regulating biological temperatures. Large amounts of energy are required to break these hydrogen bonds and convert liquid water into [water vapor](/Water_vapor). Even at a molecular level, water is in constant flux: water molecules continuously dissociate into hydrogen and [hydroxyl](/Hydroxyl) ions, only to reform again. In pure water, the concentration of these ions is balanced, resulting in a neutral [pH](/PH).

#### Organic Compounds

[Organic compounds](/Organic_compound) are the carbon-based molecules that form the backbone of life. By definition, they contain carbon bonded to at least one other element, most commonly hydrogen. With the exception of water, nearly every molecule within an organism is an organic compound. Carbon's unique ability to form [covalent bonds](/Covalent_bond) with up to four other atoms allows it to create an astonishing diversity of large and complex molecules. A single carbon atom can participate in single bonds, double bonds, or even triple bonds, leading to structures ranging from simple [methane](/Methane) to intricate ring formations like [glucose](/Glucose).

The simplest organic molecules are [hydrocarbons](/Hydrocarbon), composed solely of carbon and hydrogen. However, the true versatility of organic chemistry in biology arises when other elements, such as oxygen (O), phosphorus (P), and sulfur (S), are incorporated. These atoms can attach to the carbon backbone as [functional groups](/Functional_group), profoundly altering the compound's chemical behavior. Key functional groups found in organisms include the amino group, carboxyl group, carbonyl group, hydroxyl group, phosphate group, and sulfhydryl group. The groundbreaking [Miller–Urey experiment](/Miller%E2%80%93Urey_experiment) in 1953 provided compelling evidence that such organic compounds could indeed arise spontaneously under the conditions believed to exist on [early Earth](/Early_Earth), lending support to theories of [abiogenesis](/Abiogenesis).

#### Macromolecules

[Macromolecules](/Macromolecule) are the large, complex molecules essential for life, built from smaller repeating subunits called [monomers](/Monomer). These include sugars (forming carbohydrates), amino acids (forming proteins), and nucleotides (forming nucleic acids).

*   **Carbohydrates:** These encompass simple sugars (monosaccharides) and their polymers, such as starch and cellulose. They serve as primary energy sources and structural components.
*   **Lipids:** Unlike other macromolecules, lipids are not strictly polymers. This diverse group includes fats, phospholipids, and steroids, characterized by their largely nonpolar and [hydrophobic](/Hydrophobic) nature. They are crucial for energy storage, cell membranes, and signaling.
*   **Proteins:** The workhorses of the cell, proteins are the most diverse class of macromolecules. Built from [amino acids](/Amino_acid), they perform a vast array of functions, including acting as [enzymes](/Enzyme) to catalyze reactions, [transport proteins](/Transport_protein) to move substances, [antibodies](/Antibodies) for defense, and [structural proteins](/Structural_proteins) that provide shape and support. There are twenty common amino acids used in protein synthesis.
*   **Nucleic Acids:** These are polymers of [nucleotides](/Nucleotide) and are the carriers of genetic information. [DNA](/DNA), with its double-helix structure, stores the genetic blueprint, while [RNA](/RNA) plays critical roles in gene expression, including carrying genetic information from DNA to protein synthesis machinery.

### Cells

The [cell theory](/Cell_theory) stands as a cornerstone of biology, asserting that cells are the fundamental units of all life, that all living things are composed of one or more cells, and that all cells arise from pre-existing cells through [cell division](/Cell_division). Most cells are microscopic, typically measuring between 1 and 100 [micrometers](/Micrometre) in diameter, rendering them visible only under a [light](/Light_microscope) or [electron microscope](/Electron_microscope). Biologists generally classify cells into two main types: [eukaryotic](/Eukaryotic) cells, which possess a distinct [nucleus](/Cell_nucleus), and [prokaryotic](/Prokaryotic) cells, which lack one. Prokaryotes, such as [bacteria](/Bacterium), are predominantly [single-celled organisms](/Unicellular_organism). Eukaryotes, on the other hand, can be either single-celled or multicellular. In multicellular organisms, every cell ultimately traces its lineage back to a single [zygote](/Zygote), the product of a fertilized [egg](/Egg_(biology)).

#### Cell Structure

Every cell is enclosed by a [cell membrane](/Cell_membrane), a dynamic barrier that separates the internal [cytoplasm](/Cytoplasm) from the external environment. This membrane is a [lipid bilayer](/Lipid_bilayer), interwoven with [cholesterols](/Cholesterol) that regulate fluidity. The cell membrane is [semipermeable](/Semipermeable_membrane), allowing the passage of small molecules like oxygen and carbon dioxide while restricting larger molecules and charged particles. Embedded within this membrane are [membrane proteins](/Membrane_protein), serving diverse roles as [membrane transporters](/Membrane_transporter), enzymes, and signaling receptors. The cell membrane is also crucial for cell adhesion, maintaining [membrane potential](/Membrane_potential), and receiving external signals.

Within the cytoplasm lies a complex array of biomolecules and specialized structures known as [organelles](/Organelle) in eukaryotic cells. These organelles, often enclosed by their own membranes, perform specific functions. The [cell nucleus](/Cell_nucleus) houses the cell's DNA. [Mitochondria](/Mitochondrion) are the powerhouses, generating [adenosine triphosphate](/Adenosine_triphosphate) (ATP) to fuel cellular activities. The [endoplasmic reticulum](/Endoplasmic_reticulum) and [Golgi apparatus](/Golgi_apparatus) are involved in protein synthesis and modification, respectively. [Lysosomes](/Lysosome) contain digestive enzymes.

[Plant cells](/Plant_cell) possess additional features not found in [animal cells](/Animal_cell), including a rigid cell wall for structural support, [chloroplasts](/Chloroplast) for capturing light energy during photosynthesis, and large [vacuoles](/Vacuole) for storage and maintaining turgor pressure. Eukaryotic cells also have a [cytoskeleton](/Cytoskeleton)—a network of [microtubules](/Microtubule), [intermediate filaments](/Intermediate_filament), and [microfilaments](/Microfilament)—providing internal support, facilitating cell movement, and enabling the transport of organelles.

#### Metabolism

The maintenance of life requires a constant supply of energy, a concept encapsulated by [metabolism](/Metabolism)—the sum of all [chemical reactions](/Chemical_reactions) within an organism. Metabolism serves three primary purposes: converting food into usable energy for cellular processes, breaking down food into molecular building blocks, and eliminating metabolic byproducts. These enzyme-catalyzed reactions enable organisms to grow, reproduce, maintain their structure, and respond to their environment. Metabolic reactions are broadly categorized as [catabolic](/Catabolic) (breaking down compounds, e.g., glucose in cellular respiration) or [anabolic](/Anabolic) (building up compounds, e.g., protein synthesis). Catabolism typically releases energy, while anabolism consumes it.

Metabolic reactions are organized into [metabolic pathways](/Metabolic_pathway), where specific molecules are transformed through a series of steps, each facilitated by a unique enzyme. Enzymes act as biological [catalysts](/Catalysis), dramatically speeding up reactions by lowering the [activation energy](/Activation_energy) required. They are not consumed in the process and allow for precise [regulation](/Metabolic_pathway) of metabolic rates, enabling cells to adapt to changing conditions.

##### Cellular Respiration

[Cellular respiration](/Cellular_respiration) is a fundamental metabolic process where cells convert the chemical energy stored in nutrients into ATP, releasing waste products. These are primarily [catabolic reactions](/Catabolism) that break down larger molecules into smaller ones, releasing energy. This process is a primary means by which cells generate the energy needed for their activities.

Aerobic respiration, which uses oxygen, proceeds through four main stages in eukaryotes: [glycolysis](/Glycolysis), the [citric acid cycle](/Citric_acid_cycle), the [electron transport chain](/Electron_transport_chain), and [oxidative phosphorylation](/Oxidative_phosphorylation). Glycolysis, occurring in the cytoplasm, breaks down glucose into two pyruvate molecules, yielding a net gain of ATP. Pyruvate is then converted to acetyl-CoA, entering the citric acid cycle within the mitochondrial matrix, producing further ATP, NADH, and FADH₂. The electron transport chain and oxidative phosphorylation, occurring in the [mitochondrial cristae](/Crista), harness the energy released from electron transfer to generate a proton gradient, which drives ATP synthesis. Oxygen serves as the final [electron acceptor](/Electron_acceptor).

In the absence of oxygen, cells resort to [fermentation](/Fermentation). This anaerobic process regenerates NAD⁺, essential for glycolysis to continue, by converting pyruvate into waste products like lactic acid (in muscle cells) or ethanol and carbon dioxide (in yeast). While fermentation produces less ATP than aerobic respiration, it allows for energy production under anaerobic conditions.

##### Photosynthesis

[Photosynthesis](/Photosynthesis) is the remarkable process by which plants, algae, and cyanobacteria harness [light energy](/Light_energy) to convert [chemical energy](/Chemical_energy) into sugars. This process is the primary source of energy for most life on Earth and is responsible for maintaining the [oxygen content](/Atmospheric_oxygen) of our atmosphere. Photosynthesis involves four key stages: light absorption, electron transport, ATP synthesis, and [carbon fixation](/Carbon_fixation). Light energy absorbed by [chlorophyll](/Chlorophyll) and other pigments drives the splitting of water molecules, releasing oxygen and generating energized electrons. These electrons move through an electron transport chain, generating ATP and NADPH, which then power the [Calvin cycle](/Calvin_cycle) to fix atmospheric carbon dioxide into organic compounds.

#### Cell Signaling

[Cell signaling](/Cell_signaling) is the intricate communication system that allows cells to perceive and respond to their environment and to each other. Signals can be physical (light, electrical impulses) or chemical (ligands) that bind to specific [receptors](/Receptor_(biochemistry)). These receptors can be located on the [cell membrane](/Cell_membrane) or within the cell. Signaling pathways can be autocrine (affecting the same cell), paracrine (affecting nearby cells), juxtacrine (requiring direct cell-to-cell contact), or endocrine (using hormones transported through the bloodstream). The binding of a ligand to its receptor triggers a cascade of molecular events within the cell, known as [signal transduction](/Signal_transduction), ultimately leading to a specific cellular response.

#### Cell Cycle

The [cell cycle](/Cell_cycle) is a precisely regulated series of events that culminates in cell division, producing two daughter cells. This cycle involves DNA replication, growth, and the segregation of cellular components. In [eukaryotes](/Eukaryote), cell division occurs through either [mitosis](/Mitosis) (producing genetically identical somatic cells) or [meiosis](/Meiosis) (producing genetically diverse gametes for sexual reproduction). Prokaryotes, lacking a nucleus, divide through a simpler process called [binary fission](/Binary_fission).

##### Sexual Reproduction and Meiosis

Meiosis is fundamental to sexual reproduction in eukaryotes. Its primary role is to ensure the faithful transmission of the [genome](/Genome) to offspring. The processes of [meiotic recombination](/Genetic_recombination) and [outcrossing](/Outcrossing) are thought to be maintained due to their adaptive advantages, such as repairing [DNA damage](/DNA_damage_(naturally_occurring)) and masking deleterious recessive [mutations](/Mutation). Genetic variation, a byproduct of sexual reproduction, can confer long-term evolutionary advantages.

### Genetics

[Genetics](/Genetics) is the scientific discipline dedicated to the study of inheritance—how traits are passed from parents to offspring. [Mendelian inheritance](/Mendelian_inheritance) describes the fundamental principles articulated by Gregor Mendel, including the existence of discrete genetic units (alleles) with dominant and recessive forms, the segregation of alleles during gamete formation, and the independent assortment of genes for different traits. These principles, initially observed in pea plants, form the basis for understanding inheritance patterns. The [chromosome theory of inheritance](/Boveri%E2%80%93Sutton_chromosome_theory) later established that genes reside on chromosomes, a concept powerfully supported by Thomas Hunt Morgan's experiments with [fruit flies](/Drosophila_melanogaster).

#### Genes and DNA

A [gene](/Gene) is the fundamental unit of [heredity](/Heredity), essentially a segment of [DNA](/DNA) that carries genetic information. DNA itself is a double helix structure composed of two [polynucleotide](/Polynucleotide) chains. In eukaryotes, DNA is organized into linear [chromosomes](/Chromosome) within the [cell nucleus](/Cell_nucleus), while prokaryotes typically have a single circular chromosome located in the [nucleoid](/Nucleoid). The complete set of an organism's chromosomes constitutes its [genome](/Genome).

[DNA replication](/DNA_replication) is a [semiconservative](/Semiconservative_replication) process where each strand of the DNA molecule serves as a template for the synthesis of a new complementary strand. [Mutations](/Mutation) are changes in the DNA sequence, which can occur spontaneously or be induced by environmental factors like [mutagens](/Mutagen) (chemicals or radiation). While some mutations are harmful, others can be neutral or even beneficial, providing the raw material for [genetic variation](/Genetic_variation) and evolution.

#### Gene Expression

[Gene expression](/Gene_expression) is the process by which the genetic information encoded in DNA is used to produce functional molecules, typically proteins, that determine an organism's [phenotype](/Phenotype). This process is often described by the [central dogma of molecular biology](/Central_dogma_of_molecular_biology), which posits a flow of information from DNA to RNA to protein through [transcription](/Transcription_(genetics)) and [translation](/Translation_(genetics)), respectively.

#### Gene Regulation

The intricate process of gene expression is tightly controlled by [gene regulation](/Regulation_of_gene_expression). This regulation can occur at multiple stages, from transcription initiation to protein modification. In eukaryotes, regulatory proteins called [transcription factors](/Transcription_factor) bind to specific DNA sequences to either enhance or inhibit gene transcription. In prokaryotes, genes with related functions are often organized into [operons](/Operon), which can be switched on or off by regulatory molecules. [Epigenetic](/Epigenetics) modifications to [chromatin](/Chromatin) also play a crucial role in regulating gene expression in eukaryotes.

#### Genes, Development, and Evolution

[Development](/Developmental_biology) in multicellular organisms involves a series of transformations, from a single cell to a complex, differentiated organism. Key processes include [determination](/Cell_fate_determination) (setting a cell's fate), [differentiation](/Cellular_differentiation) (specialization into specific cell types, often involving [stem cells](/Stem_cell)), and [morphogenesis](/Morphogenesis) (the development of body form). These processes are orchestrated by a conserved set of [developmental-genetic toolkit](/Evo-devo_gene_toolkit) genes, including the influential Hox genes, which control the patterning of body segments. The interplay between genes, development, and evolutionary pressures shapes the incredible diversity of life.

### Evolution

[Evolution](/Evolution) is the unifying concept of biology, describing the change in [heritable](/Heredity) [characteristics](/Phenotypic_trait) of populations over successive [generations](/Generation). Driven by mechanisms such as [natural selection](/Natural_selection), genetic drift, and gene flow, evolution has led to the immense diversity of life we observe today.

#### Evolutionary Processes

Natural selection, as proposed by Darwin, is a key driver of evolution. It operates on the principle that individuals with traits better suited to their environment are more likely to survive and reproduce, passing those advantageous traits to their offspring. Over time, this differential reproductive success leads to the accumulation of adaptations and the gradual change of populations.

#### Speciation

[Speciation](/Speciation) is the evolutionary process by which new biological species arise. This typically occurs when populations become reproductively isolated, preventing gene flow between them. Over long periods, genetic divergence can lead to incompatibilities that render interbreeding impossible, thus marking the formation of distinct species. Geographical barriers are a common mechanism driving [allopatric speciation](/Allopatric_speciation).

#### Phylogeny

[Phylogenetics](/Phylogenetics) reconstructs the evolutionary history of life, often represented visually as a [phylogenetic tree](/Phylogenetic_tree). These trees depict the lines of descent and relationships among different species or genes. By comparing [homologous](/Homology_(biology)) features—those inherited from a common ancestor—biologists can infer evolutionary relationships. This understanding forms the basis of biological classification, organizing life into a hierarchical system of [domains](/Domain_(biology)), [kingdoms](/Kingdom_(biology)), and lower ranks. The three major [domains](/Three-domain_system) of life are Archaea, Bacteria, and Eukarya.

#### History of Life

The history of life on Earth is a vast narrative stretching back billions of years. From the earliest emergence of life around 3.5 billion years ago, through the development of prokaryotic and then eukaryotic cells, to the diversification of multicellular organisms and the emergence of complex life forms, evolution has sculpted the planet's inhabitants. Major geological eons and eras mark significant transitions, including the rise of photosynthesis, the colonization of land, and the recurrent [mass extinctions](/Extinction_event) that have reshaped the biosphere. The shared [genetic code](/Genetic_code) across all known life forms strongly suggests a [common descent](/Common_descent) from a [last universal common ancestor](/Last_universal_common_ancestor).

### Diversity

Life on Earth exhibits an astonishing diversity, broadly categorized into three [domains](/Domain_(biology)): Archaea, Bacteria, and Eukarya.

#### Bacteria and Archaea

[Bacteria](/Bacteria) and [Archaea](/Archaea) are both [prokaryotic](/Prokaryotic) microorganisms, generally lacking a nucleus and other membrane-bound organelles. While similar in size and shape, they possess distinct biochemical and genetic characteristics. Bacteria are found in virtually every habitat on Earth, playing diverse ecological roles. Archaea, initially known as extremophiles, are now recognized as widespread, inhabiting environments from deep-sea vents to the human gut. Many archaeal genes and metabolic pathways show closer relationships to eukaryotes than to bacteria.

#### Eukaryotes

[Eukaryotes](/Eukaryote) are characterized by their complex cells, which contain a nucleus and other membrane-bound organelles. This domain includes [plants](/Plant), [animals](/Animal), [fungi](/Fungi), and [protists](/Protists). Eukaryotes are thought to have arisen through endosymbiosis, where one prokaryotic cell engulfed another, leading to the development of mitochondria and chloroplasts. The major lineages of eukaryotes diversified over billions of years, giving rise to the vast array of life we see today.

*   **Plants:** Primarily multicellular, photosynthetic organisms vital for terrestrial ecosystems.
*   **Animals:** Multicellular eukaryotes characterized by their ability to move, consume organic matter, and reproduce sexually.
*   **Fungi:** Eukaryotes that obtain nutrients by external digestion, playing crucial roles as decomposers.
*   **Protists:** A diverse group of mostly unicellular eukaryotes that do not fit neatly into the other eukaryotic kingdoms.

#### Viruses

[Viruses](/Virus) are not technically cells but rather infectious agents composed of genetic material enclosed in a protein coat. They replicate by hijacking the machinery of host cells. Viruses infect all forms of life and play significant roles in evolution through horizontal gene transfer, though their exact origins remain a subject of research.

### Ecology

[Ecology](/Ecology) is the study of the intricate relationships between living organisms and their [environment](/Natural_environment), focusing on the distribution and abundance of life.

#### Ecosystems

An [ecosystem](/Ecosystem) comprises a community of living organisms (biotic components) interacting with the nonliving physical and chemical factors (abiotic components) of their environment. These systems are characterized by flows of [energy](/Energy) and cycles of [matter](/Matter). Energy typically enters through [photosynthesis](/Photosynthesis) and is transferred through food webs, while decomposers recycle nutrients.

#### Populations

A [population](/Population) is a group of individuals of the same [species](/Species) living in the same [area](/Geographical_area) and capable of interbreeding. Population dynamics are influenced by factors such as birth rates, death rates, and [carrying capacity](/Carrying_capacity)—the maximum population size an environment can sustain.

#### Communities

A [community](/Community_(ecology)) consists of multiple populations of different species interacting within a given area. These [biological interactions](/Biological_interaction), ranging from competition to mutualism, shape the structure and dynamics of the community and drive [evolution](/Evolution). [Food webs](/Food_web) illustrate the feeding relationships between species at different [trophic levels](/Trophic_level).

#### Biosphere

The [biosphere](/Biosphere) encompasses all of Earth's ecosystems, representing the sum total of all life. [Biogeochemical cycles](/Biogeochemical_cycle), such as the [carbon cycle](/Carbon_cycle) and [water cycle](/Water_cycle), describe the movement of essential elements through the biotic and abiotic components of the biosphere.

### Conservation

[Conservation biology](/Conservation_biology) is a multidisciplinary field dedicated to protecting Earth's [biodiversity](/Biodiversity). It addresses the alarming rates of [extinction](/Extinction) and seeks to maintain the evolutionary processes that generate life's diversity. The erosion of biodiversity poses a significant threat to ecosystem stability and the services they provide, necessitating urgent conservation action.